00:00:02.810 --> 00:00:04.830
A robot opened a door.

00:00:04.830 --> 00:00:08.100
Why did tens of millions of people watch this?

00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:11.850
Why is opening a door a big deal?

00:00:11.850 --> 00:00:17.250
Just five years ago there was a big robotics
competition and only one team nailed the door-opening

00:00:17.250 --> 00:00:18.250
challenge.

00:00:18.250 --> 00:00:23.099
Getting robots to perform common human tasks
was the central feature of the DARPA Robotics

00:00:23.099 --> 00:00:27.539
Challenge, a competition sponsored by the
US Department of Defense that challenged robots

00:00:27.539 --> 00:00:31.019
to perform in emergency and search and rescue
settings.

00:00:31.019 --> 00:00:36.020
In 2013, a team from the Florida Institute
for Human and Machine Cognition was the only

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:42.540
one of 16 competitors to earn a perfect score
on the door-opening task… and many of the

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.250
2-legged humanoid bots fell on their face.

00:00:47.250 --> 00:00:52.850
Just five years later, the 4-legged, well-balanced
Boston Dynamics’ SpotMini is capable of

00:00:52.850 --> 00:00:55.080
sneaking into your bedroom as you sleep.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.900
So for now, four-legs are better than two
for door-opening robots.

00:00:59.900 --> 00:01:02.190
So why did this go viral?

00:01:02.190 --> 00:01:08.259
It seems kinda creepy to some people for robots
to bypass the human-made barriers of doors.

00:01:08.259 --> 00:01:12.990
And the reason opening a door has been difficult
for robots to do is because of the Moravec

00:01:12.990 --> 00:01:13.990
Paradox.

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:17.910
Basically, that high level reasoning like
computing math equations doesn’t require

00:01:17.910 --> 00:01:25.340
much computational power but low-level reasoning
like walking on a sandy beach or opening doors,

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:28.350
requires a ton of computational resources.

00:01:28.350 --> 00:01:34.259
So things humans are able to do without thinking,
biological skills that have been refined over

00:01:34.259 --> 00:01:39.259
millions of years, are really hard to get
robots to do and things we’ve developed

00:01:39.259 --> 00:01:43.110
more recently like playing chess are a lot
easier.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:44.110
So that’s that.

00:01:44.110 --> 00:01:51.819
But that’s not all because this is Mind
Blow.

00:01:51.819 --> 00:01:55.959
The Dumbo octopus got its name because its
fins resemble the Disney character’s big

00:01:55.959 --> 00:02:01.490
ears, and for the first time we’ve seen
that baby Dumbo octopuses are actually born

00:02:01.490 --> 00:02:03.319
as tiny adults.

00:02:03.319 --> 00:02:08.490
Tim Shank of the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution in Massachusetts used a remote-operated

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:13.530
vehicle over a mile below the ocean surface
to collect samples of what appeared to be

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:16.470
egg cases -- and then one hatched.

00:02:16.470 --> 00:02:20.750
When the baby octopod emerged it had all the
characteristics of an adult.

00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:26.340
An MRI confirmed that, from the outside features
to the central nervous system, this rare baby

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:30.000
Dumbo was fully-formed and ready to go.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:39.099
He probably grew to be about 10 inches long…
and danced around like this.

00:02:39.099 --> 00:02:44.730
