00:03:09.170 --> 00:03:14.000
Israeli ramonauts have returned safely from
a 4 day mission on Mars.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.579
D-MARS.

00:03:15.579 --> 00:03:20.410
Just like HI-SEAS in Hawaii, the Mars simulation
I visited for my Planet Behind Your Eyes video,

00:03:20.410 --> 00:03:25.549
the Desert Mars Analog Ramon Station in the
Negev Desert simulates the arid, desolate

00:03:25.549 --> 00:03:27.500
environment of the Red Planet.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:32.859
Inside the Makhtesh Ramon crater, researchers
can undergo the daily routine of life on Mars

00:03:32.859 --> 00:03:35.640
and deal with its serious limitations.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:40.180
Experiments from the first mission included
determining the optimal materials for 3-D

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:45.140
printing on Mars and a psychological study
of the correlation between stress and language

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:47.049
variability in writing.

00:03:47.049 --> 00:03:52.209
It turns out that research subjects write
less and use a smaller vocabulary when they’re

00:03:52.209 --> 00:03:58.219
under stress, so the first D-MARS simulation
is helping to show how our communication changes

00:03:58.219 --> 00:04:00.250
when our environment changes.

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:04.640
The main takeaway I had from the lavanauts
I interviewed in Hawaii was that developing

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:12.959
technology to live on Mars will help us better
understand and live on Earth which seems good.

