00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:17.639
African Matabele ants frequently raid termite
colonies, and they never leave a wounded comrade

00:05:17.639 --> 00:05:18.639
behind.

00:05:18.639 --> 00:05:22.900
Research published in the Proceedings of the
Royal Society B shows that after intense termite

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:28.110
battles in which limbs are bitten off and
the ants are gravely wounded, they send pheromone

00:05:28.110 --> 00:05:30.170
signals as a cry for help.

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:34.800
Ants come to the rescue by picking up their
wounded, carrying them home, and then engaging

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:40.199
in intense “licking sessions” that prevent
infection until the wound is healed.

00:05:40.199 --> 00:05:45.169
The ants have a two-step process that determines
who can be saved and who… can’t.

00:05:45.169 --> 00:05:49.830
The mortally wounded are passed over, while
the lightly wounded are saved.

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:53.970
One model calculates that reducing the mortality
rate in termite battles allows the ants to

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:59.490
have colonies up to 29% larger than if they
continually lost soldiers -- and they demonstrate

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:02.970
to us that even insects can show compassion.

